I haven't noticed any problems with the actual physical condition of
the book, but' I HAVE been surprised at the number of internal flaws
I've found. For instance, on page 459 of book one there is a note
indicating that details of the creation and insertion of the character
'Thrain the Old' could be found in, &quot;The Fourth Phase: The 1947
Hobbit, pp. 780, 788, &amp; 791... yet 'The Fourth Phase' ends at page
762. No problem I think, I'll just look it up in the index... but then
it turns out there is no entry for this character in the index. I did
eventually track it down to page 757 and thereabouts, but there are
alot of little things like this which serve as minor hurdles to use of
the text.

That aside, lots of interesting stuff in here. Rateliff doesn't have
quite the mastery of organizing and analyzing textual history which CT
developed by the later HoME volumes, but to all appearances he has
provided an exhaustive account of the materials and thus I'm sure it
will all get sorted out and assimilated into the body of collective
Tolkien knowledge eventually. Rateliff's commentary is extensive and
he provides alot of 'external' facts (brief plot summaries of texts
Tolkien described as inspirations, translations of names from the
Eddas, et cetera). I suspect THAT has been one of the major causes of
delay in publication... Rateliff seems to have tracked down nearly
every 'loose thread' and 'passing comment' to provide background
beyond the bounds of the story itself. While this book has long been
described as a sort of 'HoME for the Hobbit', now that I've had some
time to skim through it I'd say it has at least as much in common as
Hammond &amp; Scull's Reader's Companion as it does HoME.
</POST>
