Heh.

Rateliff covers pretty much all of the various evidences we have
discussed in the past and (like CT and Anderson) states it as a given
that 'Thrain the Old' was created after the fact to explain the error
on the map. He lays out the case in exacting detail and has the
original draft texts available to back it up... showing where each
error was made and how it happened. However, the clincher for me is
that he also has it in JRRT's own words;

&quot;As for the actual runes in the book and your question p.p stands for
Thror son of Thrain. But that is an error that besides myself you
alone have spotted. On p. 202-3, the order is given as Thorin - Thrain
- Thror. The map-maker was confused and had the order Thorin - Thror -
Thrain. But even that was erroneous as dwarf-kings don't abdicate, and
the 'grandfather' was still alive when the map was made. In the sequel
it will appear that the grandfather Thror was son of an older King
Thrym (Thistlebeard). So that p.p stands for Thror Thrym's son.&quot;
-- JRR Tolkien, September 26, 1947 - previously unpublished letter to
Jennifer Paxman, responding to question about 'TH TH' runes on jar in
'Conversation with Smaug'

Tolkien says the map was in error both in the order of descent and in
stating that 'Here of old was Thrain King under the Mountain'...
because if 'Thrain' were the grandfather and thus still alive and King
when the map was made, then it couldn't have been 'of old'. He was
King at the time, not in the past. Clearly showing that the person
named on the map was meant to be Thorin's &quot;grandfather&quot;, and not some
distant ancestor.
